				<td colspan="2" height="100%" valign="top"><span class="postbody"><font size=+1>The Laughter of Thirsting Gods</font>
<br />

<br />
<i>I stand atop a cold peak, far above the battle that rages below. The feint cries of dying elves reach my ears and my minds eye briefly envisions one of my Forsaken brothers taking a head as a symbol of his triumph. The snow at my feet is a slushy pink. Pools of blood steam under the glare of the afternoon sun. I am watching a horrible thing: an ancient elemental of ice rips into fleeing ranks of human soldiers with hate cold and eons old. What is this thing we have bound to our service? See how it seems to rip souls from flesh even before the victims fall lifeless to the earth? Such idle thoughts slip away as easily as they come. I do not care what pacts the Orcish warlocks have struck, nor the price: it shall not be paid in </i>my<i> blood.
<br />

<br />
I tighten my grasp on my frost-kissed sword and turn my thoughts once more upon the enemy. The Alliance is shattered. They do not even pause in their flight to recover their dead, much to my hungry brothers delight. Final victory in this wasteland is only a matter of time. They flee north to the keep that will soon become a charnel house. For a moment I feel a tinge of anticipation in my dead fingers, but perhaps that is merely the cold.
<br />

<br />
No matter, for now I ride. To the north. To victory.</i>
<br />

<br />
<b>Battlegrounds pwn.</b>
<br />

<br />
Despite all of the pre-release blogs touting a flawed design, horrible wait times, and crashing servers, Blizzard got Battlegrounds right. Predictions of failure proved to be nothing more than wishful thinking of the fatalist die-hards. After all, if those blogs and guild pages didnt have something to bitch about they might not get a chance to become game designers would they? (A discussion for another update: why do so many WoW players want or expect to see Blizzard fail?)
<br />

<br />
Prior to Battlegrounds, Science of War had taken only tentative steps into the world of PvP. Our primary motivation is beating the PvE game and we center our guild efforts on learning and mastering PvE encounters. Battlegrounds, however, has given us something new to sink our teeth into and so far the dogs of war are pleased. In fact, weve had to ask several of our younger members to make sure they arent losing too much focus on the task of leveling to 60. Its a great system, full of charm and challenge and uh-something alliterative that means thematic. Battlegrounds hits fun on all cylinders.
<br />

<br />
So what makes BG work? I dont really want to completely dissect Battlegrounds. Well, I doit would be funbut I dont want to do it right now. Lets look at the broad picture.
<br />

<br />
<b>Class Interaction &amp; Teamwork:</b> Tanks lead the charge, rogues stealth behind enemy lines, warlocks call down demons: World of Warcrafts class roles really shine in Battlegrounds. The most successful CTF teams utilize strategies that emphasis class roles. For example: Druids make good flag carriers because of their ability to move fast, Hunters make excellent screens for the flag carrier because of their ability to snare pursuing enemies, Rogues make excellent recon because of their ability to survey the battlefield undetected, and so on. Similarly, the Alterac Valley scenario relies on large groups of players cooperating in a way that maximizes their class effectiveness. Tanks backed by healers carve a wave of death into the ranks of unorganized defenders. Playing your class well and being rewarded for it is fun. Knowing you just did something through a genius moment of teamwork is crazy fun.
<br />
 
<br />
<b>Lots of Variety:</b> Im blown away by the amount of variety in the two Battlegrounds scenarios. Alterac Valley is brimming with quests and roles within roles. Any class can choose to perform supporting quests, such as clearing a nearby mine of Kobolds and then providing the armys smith with supplies. You can capture enemy fortifications, escort sorcerers to raise fell allies, or rescue key military advisors to bolster your selection of weapons. Alterac Valley could easily have simply been take and hold locations A, B, and C FTW! but instead its a dynamic storyline that unfolds a different way each time its played. Warsong Gulch, the CTF scenario, lacks the variety of Alterac, but has an extremely well designed map. There are many strategies for mounting an effective offense or defense and that alone will provide for many hours replayability. 
<br />

<br />
<b>Thematic Content:</b> Battlegrounds is full of Warcrafty-ness. In Alterac Valley, each side has to mine and collect resources to equip NPC soldiers with upgraded weapons. Warlocks demand blood sacrifices. Wolf riders patrol the valleys and gryphon riders patrol the skies. Due to the large numbers of weaker NPC soldiers involved in the scenario, the battles feel epic and your character's role feels significant. With so many of us playing MMOs to briefly escape the real world or indulge in our romantic side, the strength of theme in battlegrounds really helps make the experience exciting. If I had envisioned playing Warcraft 3 from the point of view of one of the heros I probably wouldnt have come this close to hitting the mark.
<br />

<br />
<b>Endless Slaughter:</b> Lets face it: taking out another player is fun. Few opponents of PvP dislike it because they dont like killing another player. What they don't like is getting killed. They dont like getting ganked when theyre focused on some quest. They dont like the idea that their skills might not be as good as another player and they dont want to be reminded of that fact. Battlegrounds helps take the sting out of PvP. First, the penalty for dying is nil. You die and within 30 seconds you are back in the action. Second, the battle takes place in a fixed area on straightforward terms. You can easily leave and remove yourself from PvP. Third, you are surrounded by allies. If you play smart, youll always have someone to watch your back. Getting unexpectedly ganked is rare. Essentially, Battlegrounds puts control over the PvP experience in the hands of the player.
<br />

<br />
Those are just a few reasons why I think Battlegrounds works. There are a lot more. This really is the patch youve been waiting for. Get it, get in, get to the killing.
<br />

<br />
Post your own comments about Battlegrounds in our forum!</span><br /><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
